      "text": "1 All hardware being checked\n2 when hardware are checked by BIOS it points to MBR(Master Boot Record)(very first sector of our HDD).\n3 MBR stores pointer and that pointer point us to something called as GRUB.\n4 using GRUB we can select which kernel or where our OS can start or where our kernel menu is.\n5 once kernel is selected now our kernel boots or starts.\n6 technically the first process that is starting in our system in our LINUX machine is a kernel that actually loads from the HDD\n    and goes to the processor to start as a complete process to load our OS.\n7 Now our Kernel is set that take some parameter, we can pass the values between 0 to 6 or 0 to 7, these parameter called as our\ninit parameter\n8 lets say we have K function that take parameter like 0 -> lets say 0 means sut down\n                1 -> means start in a single user mode\n                2 -> start in a multi user mode so that multiple user, who can use the system at very same time\n                3 -> means start the system here but the display shoudl be visible somewhere else (display forwarding).\n\n                basically from these init values what kernel will do is decided.\n\n9 Run Level (Last step)-> now the kernel is started with the given init parameter, now we can have a interaction with our base hardware\n    next things is setting up multiple application that can give it a structure of OS, to start this there would be some priority we can't\nstart anyting and everything, we can't start everything like browser is turning ON, gaming is turning On everything is turning ON, that \nwill be pretty weird, but again there are something that are supppose to start. For example our Network is suppose to start, our Firewall\nis support to start, our GUI is supppose to start, all other thing that give OS a shape, they are suppose to start. and within these\nfeatures also there is certain priorities, these priorities are called as RUN level. Basically Run level is nothing we are putting some\napplications on startup. LIke when the system boots please start these services as well.\nWhy Priority ? First network will start or Firewall?\nif our network is started first which means people can come and connect to our system and our firewall is not yet started which means there\nis a possiblity of attack though there is a momentory possiblity but there is a possiblity of attack, that is why we will start Firewall\nbefore starting the network, Likewise GUI will be end or toward end in priority. setup everything first then load my GUI its pretty fine.\nSo priorities of running everything is called Run Level. and all these 6 steps make up our Boot process.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1 All hardware being checked\n2 when hardware are checked by BIOS it points to MBR(Master Boot Record)(very first sector of our HDD).\n3 MBR stores pointer and that pointer point us to something called as GRUB.\n4 using GRUB we can select which kernel or where our OS can start or where our kernel menu is.\n5 once kernel is selected now our kernel boots or starts.\n6 technically the first process that is starting in our system in our LINUX machine is a kernel that actually loads from the HDD\n    and goes to the processor to start as a complete process to load our OS.\n7 Now our Kernel is set that take some parameter, we can pass the values between 0 to 6 or 0 to 7, these parameter called as our\ninit parameter\n8 lets say we have K function that take parameter like 0 -> lets say 0 means sut down\n                1 -> means start in a single user mode\n                2 -> start in a multi user mode so that multiple user, who can use the system at very same time\n                3 -> means start the system here but the display shoudl be visible somewhere else (display forwarding).\n\n                basically from these init values what kernel will do is decided.\n\n9 Run Level (Last step)-> now the kernel is started with the given init parameter, now we can have a interaction with our base hardware\n    next things is setting up multiple application that can give it a structure of OS, to start this there would be some priority we can't\nstart anyting and everything, we can't start everything like browser is turning ON, gaming is turning On everything is turning ON, that \nwill be pretty weird, but again there are something that are supppose to start. For example our Network is suppose to start, our Firewall\nis support to start, our GUI is supppose to start, all other thing that give OS a shape, they are suppose to start. and within these\nfeatures also there is certain priorities, these priorities are called as RUN level. Basically Run level is nothing we are putting some\napplications on startup. LIke when the system boots please start these services as well.\nWhy Priority ? First network will start or Firewall?\nif our network is started first which means people can come and connect to our system and our firewall is not yet started which means there\nis a possiblity of attack though there is a momentory possiblity but there is a possiblity of attack, that is why we will start Firewall\nbefore starting the network, Likewise GUI will be end or toward end in priority. setup everything first then load my GUI its pretty fine.\nSo priorities of running everything is called Run Level. and all these 6 steps make up our Boot process.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "uEPOOI0TiDWa8KYXCFOn4",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 945.7171553480769,
      "y": 18000.397330296,
      "width": 170.6759033203125,
      "height": 64.66624083386702,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
