      "updated": 1771267989253,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "What is GRUB\n",
      "fontSize": 25.86649633354681,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "What is GRUB\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "HW9s3KkYbgQ6lAMLIYT3D",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 984.3470806635548,
      "y": 18064.134589197824,
      "width": 1463,
      "height": 150,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bMa",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 461391666,
      "version": 998,
      "versionNonce": 1439308846,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771268215647,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "without kernal we can't use OS & other Application software on top of that. SO first thing that is required to be running is our\nKernel, In modern system we can have multiple kernel at the very first time but at the running time we have to choose whihc\nkernel we have to start our system, In earlier time grub was not there at that time there was something called as LILO(Linux Loader).\nLILO will just point us to the kernel at that time there was only used single kernel Now a days multiple kernel and we have to \nchoose which kernel we have to boot from with the help of GRUB we do that. By default whatever OS we install comes with a \nsingle kernel.(35:00)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "without kernal we can't use OS & other Application software on top of that. SO first thing that is required to be running is our\nKernel, In modern system we can have multiple kernel at the very first time but at the running time we have to choose whihc\nkernel we have to start our system, In earlier time grub was not there at that time there was something called as LILO(Linux Loader).\nLILO will just point us to the kernel at that time there was only used single kernel Now a days multiple kernel and we have to \nchoose which kernel we have to boot from with the help of GRUB we do that. By default whatever OS we install comes with a \nsingle kernel.(35:00)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "lywJKpaSag6_n9Z6livO7",
