    {
      "id": "b9IsR6whmZjs-9N4x73-L",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 960.3285809403278,
      "y": 20787.573080365546,
      "width": 1309,
      "height": 300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bOK",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1700228294,
      "version": 1311,
      "versionNonce": 332146650,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771439353621,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "whoami -> tells which user we are loged in with, what is current user name, root user is big daddy over here, its a \nfather of all users.\n\nLinux system is more like a Home and in this home there is a child's room, kitche, guest room, other rooms, and there\nis a room of parents. Parents have access to everything, we can't go to Dad's room and take a cigrate from there and\nsmoke it up. But our Dad can come in our room and use our playstation or work on our Laptop, He can do anything, \nPermissions work more like this, When we are learning LINUX at that level where in we want to go everywhere, we have to\nmake everything, break everything, we need every permission, And if we dont want to stuck on permission again and again\nlike we are switching one room to other and seeking for permission, we don't have to wait for it. So rather work as\na parent(big daddy), go to any room and do whatever you want, that is why we want to work as root user.\n\nEverytime when we start our terminal the first command that we are suppose to run is",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "whoami -> tells which user we are loged in with, what is current user name, root user is big daddy over here, its a \nfather of all users.\n\nLinux system is more like a Home and in this home there is a child's room, kitche, guest room, other rooms, and there\nis a room of parents. Parents have access to everything, we can't go to Dad's room and take a cigrate from there and\nsmoke it up. But our Dad can come in our room and use our playstation or work on our Laptop, He can do anything, \nPermissions work more like this, When we are learning LINUX at that level where in we want to go everywhere, we have to\nmake everything, break everything, we need every permission, And if we dont want to stuck on permission again and again\nlike we are switching one room to other and seeking for permission, we don't have to wait for it. So rather work as\na parent(big daddy), go to any room and do whatever you want, that is why we want to work as root user.\n\nEverytime when we start our terminal the first command that we are suppose to run is",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "kNZmgB270wujcEmM-3Q6v",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 995.1785991089336,
      "y": 21124.833436470188,
      "width": 1265,
      "height": 975,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bOM",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1671356742,
      "version": 2155,
      "versionNonce": 1315210051,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771955679417,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "sudo su -> su means switch user, whenever we will not specifiy which user, it will automatically switches to\n           root user.\n\nwhoami -> now give root\nps -> it will give all the running process in our system right now, A bash process is running because our terminal\n      is ON,  PS process is running, because we started the PS command. We all know there are more processes than\n      this running, there is some process running, that is starting our GUI. there is time displayed in one corner\nof our system, which measn date and time process is running, there are othre such process running on background. So\nthere are lot more process running.\n        \n      but currently it is just showing us the processes that are started by our user in our particular terminal.\n\nWe can give 3 thing in a cli mode\ncommand\nflag\nparameter\n\nps command takes multiple flags\n\nps -aux\n\n\ninit 0 -> means we are passing to kernal shut down\n\npwd -> present working directory -> /home/ubuntu something like this\ncd -> change directory\npwd -> /root -> this directory is the home directory or the room of our root user\n\nearlier because we loged in as ubuntu user or our own username, so by default we landed to the room\nof whatever our username was. So we switched user but we never change directory, whenever we hit cd\ncommand without any parameter it will make us reach to the home location. Every user has a home\n\ncd / -> / is the location from where in Linux every path, every file, every location, everything in Linux\nstarts from /.\n\nls -> to list what all there in my / directory, there is nothing called as folder, So we have directories and\n    files only\n\ninit commands can be done from any directory, commands are not directory specific.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "sudo su -> su means switch user, whenever we will not specifiy which user, it will automatically switches to\n           root user.\n\nwhoami -> now give root\nps -> it will give all the running process in our system right now, A bash process is running because our terminal\n      is ON,  PS process is running, because we started the PS command. We all know there are more processes than\n      this running, there is some process running, that is starting our GUI. there is time displayed in one corner\nof our system, which measn date and time process is running, there are othre such process running on background. So\nthere are lot more process running.\n        \n      but currently it is just showing us the processes that are started by our user in our particular terminal.\n\nWe can give 3 thing in a cli mode\ncommand\nflag\nparameter\n\nps command takes multiple flags\n\nps -aux\n\n\ninit 0 -> means we are passing to kernal shut down\n\npwd -> present working directory -> /home/ubuntu something like this\ncd -> change directory\npwd -> /root -> this directory is the home directory or the room of our root user\n\nearlier because we loged in as ubuntu user or our own username, so by default we landed to the room\nof whatever our username was. So we switched user but we never change directory, whenever we hit cd\ncommand without any parameter it will make us reach to the home location. Every user has a home\n\ncd / -> / is the location from where in Linux every path, every file, every location, everything in Linux\nstarts from /.\n\nls -> to list what all there in my / directory, there is nothing called as folder, So we have directories and\n    files only\n\ninit commands can be done from any directory, commands are not directory specific.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "luU6JDZIfCM0eKKum7Yx7",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 945.6944051713419,
      "y": 22158.370136427915,
      "width": 451,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bON",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 425250435,
      "version": 51,
      "versionNonce": 1546463075,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771955705371,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How to Know this is a directory or File ?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How to Know this is a directory or File ?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "qA184jGbrHINIAKyeJDgF",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1021.1123739213419,
      "y": 22223.733417677915,
      "width": 1452,
      "height": 2325,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bOO",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 90415789,
      "version": 6914,
      "versionNonce": 241275267,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771960935628,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "To Know this we will run \nls -l -> by -l flag it will list everything but in a more descriptive, in a more detailed way\n\nif the line starts with - then its a file, if its starts with d its a directory, if its starts with\nl then its sim link we will talk later for this\n\ninside / we will get main(imp) directory which are \n    home\n    root\n    bin\n    sbin\n    usr\n    var\n    proc\n    etc\n\nhome will have home for every user that we create. Lets say we created ubuntu user. So there will be a\nfolder created inside home and that folder will be named as ubuntu. If we create a new user named as rahul\nUser then it will create rahul folder inside home and that rahul will have all the permission to do anything\nand everything inside that rahul directory\n\n/home/ubuntu -> if ubuntu user want to do anything in our system it can do only inside /home/ubuntu but right\nnow we don't just want to have fun inside this directory, We want to have fun outside the directory also, like\ncurrently we are in slash, we want to have fun here as well, that is why we are root user so that we can go\nanywhere and do any kind of fun, Fun as in read the files, write the files, delete thef files, create the files\nall of that.\n\nhome directory will have home for all the users that we have apart from one user, that user is root.\nroot user has different home called as /root -> /root is home directory for root user.\n\nEven if we are root user, we can do anything, anywhere that we want, but if we want to create some files\nvery specific to root user then we will create in /root directory\n\n/ -> is for entire system if we will do anything in / folder then it will impact entire system.\n\nroot is like admin user, Now my admin want to create certain files which is just there for admin to see.\nor admin to use, it has no purpose of impacting all the other users or my entire system.\nI want to create some management files, some tracking files, some log files we will create in our /root\ndirectory\n\nbin -> it stores all the binaries, Binaries are the executable files, the software that we run for example\nrun command date\n\n    date -> it will give todays date and time UTC format\n    to get this date and time , it is pretty obvious some code might have been executed, so where was the\n    code file, where was the code written, where was the software that is executed, that software that\n    got executed is stored inside generally in bin there are other location as well for softwares\n    , So whatever softwares which we are having in our system, they are. stored inside bin.\n\ncd /bin -> go inside bin folder\nls -> it will give all the softwares that our system has\nls date -> it will show that date software exist or not? \n\n\nsbin -> all the software generally present in bin , Software can be other location as well For example one of\nthe popular location, another location is sbin, or there is another folder here is called usr, inside usr\nwe will find two directories which are bin and sbin, both of these also store software, why there are multiple\nlocations\n    bin -> general software for every user \n    sbin -> system level software(like drivers,software that we dont usually run, they are required to support and run our system ).\n    usr/bin -> general software specific to a particular user\n    usr/sbin -> system level software specific to a particular user.\n\n\netc -> it is very imp directory, as a developer we will deal with it almost on a daily basis, why it is needed ?\n    because, whenever we write a software there will be multiple file like  one is executable file other is \n    configuration file, other is log file so there are various files from which we are combining together for one\n    single software, So if we will put all these thing inside bin whihc have many executable and we will write this\n    here also then things will be very messy, So we will put executable in bin and configuration file in etc\n    so that things will be managed, we can put somewhere else as well but as a good developer we need to know \n    where we need to put which thing so that things will be managable. hence we will put configuration files inside\n    etc folder. So where will our log files exist, lets say who came on my web server, how many times our web server\n    got invoked or how many users were there, what is it returing? is it returing 404 page not found all these things\n    are stored in logs, our kernel logs, system logs all the logs stores in logs, so these logs go inside specific\n    directory called var.\n\nvar -> it stores all the logs. most imp one inside this directory is /var/log\n\nproc ->\ncd /proc\nls -> there are multiple directories created, and those directories having certain number. what\n    are these number, these numbers are our process ids. whatever process we are running.\n\nif we will run again ls then we will see atleast one directory where number is changed\n\nwhy it happen -> when we run a command it becomes a process, every process has a process id, with\nthat particular id, the directory gets created in our proc. and in that directory everything related\nto our process is there. and when the process gets killed or the process is done, purpose of ls\nis list everything, once every listing is done, the directory gets deleted, the next time I run ls\nagain the new directory gets created with a new process id with a new number, likewise other directories\ncreated for other processes as well. and these directories holds the info related to that process, everything\nthat process needs or creates or when the process is running, whatever is happening, it is happening inside\nthis directory.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "To Know this we will run \nls -l -> by -l flag it will list everything but in a more descriptive, in a more detailed way\n\nif the line starts with - then its a file, if its starts with d its a directory, if its starts with\nl then its sim link we will talk later for this\n\ninside / we will get main(imp) directory which are \n    home\n    root\n    bin\n    sbin\n    usr\n    var\n    proc\n    etc\n\nhome will have home for every user that we create. Lets say we created ubuntu user. So there will be a\nfolder created inside home and that folder will be named as ubuntu. If we create a new user named as rahul\nUser then it will create rahul folder inside home and that rahul will have all the permission to do anything\nand everything inside that rahul directory\n\n/home/ubuntu -> if ubuntu user want to do anything in our system it can do only inside /home/ubuntu but right\nnow we don't just want to have fun inside this directory, We want to have fun outside the directory also, like\ncurrently we are in slash, we want to have fun here as well, that is why we are root user so that we can go\nanywhere and do any kind of fun, Fun as in read the files, write the files, delete thef files, create the files\nall of that.\n\nhome directory will have home for all the users that we have apart from one user, that user is root.\nroot user has different home called as /root -> /root is home directory for root user.\n\nEven if we are root user, we can do anything, anywhere that we want, but if we want to create some files\nvery specific to root user then we will create in /root directory\n\n/ -> is for entire system if we will do anything in / folder then it will impact entire system.\n\nroot is like admin user, Now my admin want to create certain files which is just there for admin to see.\nor admin to use, it has no purpose of impacting all the other users or my entire system.\nI want to create some management files, some tracking files, some log files we will create in our /root\ndirectory\n\nbin -> it stores all the binaries, Binaries are the executable files, the software that we run for example\nrun command date\n\n    date -> it will give todays date and time UTC format\n    to get this date and time , it is pretty obvious some code might have been executed, so where was the\n    code file, where was the code written, where was the software that is executed, that software that\n    got executed is stored inside generally in bin there are other location as well for softwares\n    , So whatever softwares which we are having in our system, they are. stored inside bin.\n\ncd /bin -> go inside bin folder\nls -> it will give all the softwares that our system has\nls date -> it will show that date software exist or not? \n\n\nsbin -> all the software generally present in bin , Software can be other location as well For example one of\nthe popular location, another location is sbin, or there is another folder here is called usr, inside usr\nwe will find two directories which are bin and sbin, both of these also store software, why there are multiple\nlocations\n    bin -> general software for every user \n    sbin -> system level software(like drivers,software that we dont usually run, they are required to support and run our system ).\n    usr/bin -> general software specific to a particular user\n    usr/sbin -> system level software specific to a particular user.\n\n\netc -> it is very imp directory, as a developer we will deal with it almost on a daily basis, why it is needed ?\n    because, whenever we write a software there will be multiple file like  one is executable file other is \n    configuration file, other is log file so there are various files from which we are combining together for one\n    single software, So if we will put all these thing inside bin whihc have many executable and we will write this\n    here also then things will be very messy, So we will put executable in bin and configuration file in etc\n    so that things will be managed, we can put somewhere else as well but as a good developer we need to know \n    where we need to put which thing so that things will be managable. hence we will put configuration files inside\n    etc folder. So where will our log files exist, lets say who came on my web server, how many times our web server\n    got invoked or how many users were there, what is it returing? is it returing 404 page not found all these things\n    are stored in logs, our kernel logs, system logs all the logs stores in logs, so these logs go inside specific\n    directory called var.\n\nvar -> it stores all the logs. most imp one inside this directory is /var/log\n\nproc ->\ncd /proc\nls -> there are multiple directories created, and those directories having certain number. what\n    are these number, these numbers are our process ids. whatever process we are running.\n\nif we will run again ls then we will see atleast one directory where number is changed\n\nwhy it happen -> when we run a command it becomes a process, every process has a process id, with\nthat particular id, the directory gets created in our proc. and in that directory everything related\nto our process is there. and when the process gets killed or the process is done, purpose of ls\nis list everything, once every listing is done, the directory gets deleted, the next time I run ls\nagain the new directory gets created with a new process id with a new number, likewise other directories\ncreated for other processes as well. and these directories holds the info related to that process, everything\nthat process needs or creates or when the process is running, whatever is happening, it is happening inside\nthis directory.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
