    {
      "id": "i2OiGXOucQ1HZs29t8V7W",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 998.1904989213419,
      "y": 24660.905292677915,
      "width": 1188,
      "height": 325,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bOV",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 380543203,
      "version": 1631,
      "versionNonce": 816154541,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771961728478,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "In RAM, which means we are sitting inside RAM now, we are not in hardisk, By going inside our\nproc directory, technically we are on RAM. So whatever we are doing is called as RAM reading. RAM reading\nis a very advance concept of LINUX, which is taught as part of system forensics. When some criminal\ninvestigation is done they try to seize their systems, Even when the things are deleted or something like\nthat, or even when the system is powered off, See RAM is made up of some capacitors, some electricity\nsome charge is still there, So they try to read RAM reading and see whatever they can fetch from the current\nprocesses, running processes. Even when they find some tiny detail like some images, some coordinates they\ntry to recover that data by RAM reading. We can also check which process taking which memory, we can see\nwhihc variable is taking what time like 4 byte or 8 bytes live rather that reading on book.\nSo this is the magic of RAM reading, we can go, see live that when our process is running what exactly\nis happening in the background.\nTo read our RAM we can inside proc, basically our RAM is connected to our HDD via this directory called as\nproc, what this process is called, what mounting is that also we will discuss later",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "In RAM, which means we are sitting inside RAM now, we are not in hardisk, By going inside our\nproc directory, technically we are on RAM. So whatever we are doing is called as RAM reading. RAM reading\nis a very advance concept of LINUX, which is taught as part of system forensics. When some criminal\ninvestigation is done they try to seize their systems, Even when the things are deleted or something like\nthat, or even when the system is powered off, See RAM is made up of some capacitors, some electricity\nsome charge is still there, So they try to read RAM reading and see whatever they can fetch from the current\nprocesses, running processes. Even when they find some tiny detail like some images, some coordinates they\ntry to recover that data by RAM reading. We can also check which process taking which memory, we can see\nwhihc variable is taking what time like 4 byte or 8 bytes live rather that reading on book.\nSo this is the magic of RAM reading, we can go, see live that when our process is running what exactly\nis happening in the background.\nTo read our RAM we can inside proc, basically our RAM is connected to our HDD via this directory called as\nproc, what this process is called, what mounting is that also we will discuss later",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
