    {
      "id": "2zKcDOulGpdVUYZbnVIIZ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1069.4481520083325,
      "y": 30521.93792047001,
      "width": 1023,
      "height": 300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bPW",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 986557146,
      "version": 1204,
      "versionNonce": 1719877658,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1772083836151,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "When we open a MP4 file with VLC media player, it plays a video, what will happend if we will\nopen same Mp4 file with a text editor, it will open like a text\n\nthis directory(file) also with a certain specific type and when we open it with a specific\nsoftware that software is our file manager, filemanager makes us see this file in a certain \nway that it looks like a directory, it looks like we are going inside it, We are not going\ninside it, we are just reading the content of that file, We are just reading the pointers\nwhich are displayed with certain icons.\n\nIn IT world two defintions are easiest\ndatatype -> type of data is called data type\nmetadata -> data about data",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "When we open a MP4 file with VLC media player, it plays a video, what will happend if we will\nopen same Mp4 file with a text editor, it will open like a text\n\nthis directory(file) also with a certain specific type and when we open it with a specific\nsoftware that software is our file manager, filemanager makes us see this file in a certain \nway that it looks like a directory, it looks like we are going inside it, We are not going\ninside it, we are just reading the content of that file, We are just reading the pointers\nwhich are displayed with certain icons.\n\nIn IT world two defintions are easiest\ndatatype -> type of data is called data type\nmetadata -> data about data",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "UYDrEXaHuWppef6crqvF-",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1135.3782238745252,
      "y": 29465.48974778195,
      "width": 1100,
      "height": 800,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bPX",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1395899418,
      "version": 2013,
      "versionNonce": 1777735878,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1772084218580,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "ls -lhi ->  it will give random number that is pointer that we talking about. this i is inode number\n            which is very imp in terms of interview. Like how you will see your inode -> via ls -i\nls -i -> gives the inode number\n\nwhat is that pointer -> exact address of the hardisk sector where it is stored, where the\nfile is stored So every time we read a file from HDD? how file will read from HDD?\n\nLets say we have HDD and lets say we start reading files from one sector to another, there\nis a starting pointer we start reading the files, and somewhere in one of the sectors there\nwill be a character written whihc is called as eof(end of file). When we reach the end of file\nit marks as the file is ended over here. But what if we write a software whihc can read each\nand every sector, reading each and every sector of a HDD is very simple and can skip every\neof, that is a way of passing security, this is used in hacking also if software can skip\neof then they can read evrything inside the HDD beyond the permissions.\n\n\nif we have one file f1 inside /root and we want to read this file we can read this via\n\ncat f1 or cat ./f1\n\nwhat is . here and what is .. in cd .. -> \n\ncd -> now we will in /root\nls -a ->  this will display hidden files also, there are two hidden files that we can seee\n          one is . and another one is ..\n          . is a pointer to current location its own folder\n          .. is always a pointer to previous location\n        \n        whatever the parent pointer, .. is going to point that\n\n        cd d1 -> we are giving the pointer name in whihc we want to go\n        cd .. -> parent directory, every directory would have this .. as a hidden file",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "ls -lhi ->  it will give random number that is pointer that we talking about. this i is inode number\n            which is very imp in terms of interview. Like how you will see your inode -> via ls -i\nls -i -> gives the inode number\n\nwhat is that pointer -> exact address of the hardisk sector where it is stored, where the\nfile is stored So every time we read a file from HDD? how file will read from HDD?\n\nLets say we have HDD and lets say we start reading files from one sector to another, there\nis a starting pointer we start reading the files, and somewhere in one of the sectors there\nwill be a character written whihc is called as eof(end of file). When we reach the end of file\nit marks as the file is ended over here. But what if we write a software whihc can read each\nand every sector, reading each and every sector of a HDD is very simple and can skip every\neof, that is a way of passing security, this is used in hacking also if software can skip\neof then they can read evrything inside the HDD beyond the permissions.\n\n\nif we have one file f1 inside /root and we want to read this file we can read this via\n\ncat f1 or cat ./f1\n\nwhat is . here and what is .. in cd .. -> \n\ncd -> now we will in /root\nls -a ->  this will display hidden files also, there are two hidden files that we can seee\n          one is . and another one is ..\n          . is a pointer to current location its own folder\n          .. is always a pointer to previous location\n        \n        whatever the parent pointer, .. is going to point that\n\n        cd d1 -> we are giving the pointer name in whihc we want to go\n        cd .. -> parent directory, every directory would have this .. as a hidden file",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "tV67A6PlSyhxrdgT7kftK",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1013.3583893758962,
      "y": 31785.738118672336,
      "width": 11,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
